atus and validity of dualism. Of special interest are developing alternatives to traditional dualistic categories through an innovative, new approach based on biological naturalism; challenges to the dualism of people and things; the imperfectness and subjectivity of perception; and the overcoming the dualism of philosophy and science.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aDeterminism (Philosophy)vCongresses. 0aDualismvCongresses. 0aKnowledge, Theory ofvCongresses. 0aPhilosophy, Moderny19th centuryvCongresses. 0aRationalismvCongresses. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Social Philosophy. 4aSociology : Social Thought. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aDonath, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee, Richard E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPickering, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSearle, John R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWallerstein, Immanuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438434094423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438434094/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles